Using Node.js v25.7.0 on WIndows, got a project, runnng cdn of tailwind, wanna move to the "offline" version, give me the commands and everything for this

Moving away from the CDN to a local installation gives you faster page loads, the ability to work offline, and access to Tailwind's full feature set. Since you are using a modern Node environment, you can use Tailwind v4, which is incredibly fast and requires zero configuration to get started.

Here is how to set up the local CLI build:

1
Initialize your Node project
Skip if you already have a package.json
Open your terminal in your project folder and run:

Bash
npm init -y
2
Install Tailwind CSS v4
Install the core framework and the new CLI tool as dependencies:

Bash
npm install tailwindcss @tailwindcss/cli
3
Create an input CSS file
Create a folder named src (if you don't have one) and create a file inside it named input.css. Add this single line to import Tailwind:

CSS
@import "tailwindcss";
4
Swap the CDN for the local file in your HTML
Remove the CDN script tag (<script src="[https://cdn.tailwindcss.com](https://cdn.tailwindcss.com)"></script>) from your HTML files. Replace it with a standard CSS link pointing to the compiled file we are about to generate:

HTML

5
Run the build process
Start the CLI compiler in your terminal. This command reads your input file, scans your HTML for Tailwind classes, and generates the output.css file:

Bash
npx @tailwindcss/cli -i ./src/input.css -o ./src/output.css --watch
Leave this command running in the background. The --watch flag ensures it instantly rebuilds your CSS every time you save an HTML file.


Note on configuration: Tailwind v4 automatically scans your project directory for HTML and JavaScript files to find the classes you use, so you no longer need a tailwind.config.js file for a standard setup.

It makes my thing slightly broken, help

I see exactly what is going on in image_492342.png—you have a "ghost button" at the bottom of your form!

When you clicked that empty white space at the bottom, it triggered the browser's native "Please fill in this field." tooltip for the empty password field. This confirms your submit button is sitting exactly where it should be, but it has become completely invisible.

Here is exactly why this happens when moving off the CDN to a local Tailwind v4 setup:

The Preflight Reset: By default, Tailwind applies a global reset that strips standard browser styling from elements, which includes setting all <button> backgrounds to transparent.

The Lost Configuration: When you used the CDN, you likely defined your custom colors (like the primary color for that button) inside a JavaScript <script> tag. When you deleted the CDN scripts to switch to the local CLI, those custom color definitions were deleted along with it.

The Result: Because the compiler no longer knows what your custom background class (e.g., bg-primary or bg-brand-blue) means, it ignores it. Your button falls back to Tailwind's default transparent background. If your button text is white (text-white), it completely vanishes against the white container!

The Fix
To get your button back, you need to bring your custom colors into your new v4 setup. Tailwind CSS v4 transitioned away from JavaScript-based configurations and now uses a CSS-based configuration system.

You need to define your custom colors directly in your CSS using the new @theme directive.

Open the src/input.css file we created earlier and add your custom colors back in like this:

CSS
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  /* Replace this hex code with your actual button color */
  --color-primary: #1d4ed8; 
}
Note on naming: If your HTML uses a class like bg-brand, you would name your variable --color-brand.

As long as your CLI --watch command is still running in the background, saving this file will instantly regenerate your output.css and your button will reappear on the screen.

