No I mean, the thing for the input.css

Ah, my apologies! You meant the configuration block to fix your custom styling.

Based on the Tailwind configuration script you had embedded in your login.html file, here is exactly what needs to go into your src/input.css file for Tailwind v4.  
HTML

We need to translate your custom colors, font, and animations into CSS variables inside the new @theme block.

Copy and paste this entire block into your src/input.css:

CSS
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  /* Custom Pink Color Palette */
  --color-custom-pink-50: #fdf2f8;
  --color-custom-pink-100: #fce7f3;
  --color-custom-pink-200: #fbcfe8;
  --color-custom-pink-300: #f9a8d4;
  --color-custom-pink-400: #f472b6;
  --color-custom-pink-500: #ec4899;
  --color-custom-pink-600: #db2777;
  --color-custom-pink-700: #be185d;
  --color-custom-pink-800: #9d174d;
  --color-custom-pink-900: #831843;

  /* Font Family Override */
  --font-sans: "Inter", sans-serif;

  /* Custom Animation */
  --animate-fade-in-up: fadeInUp 0.6s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1) forwards;
}

/* Custom Keyframes */
@keyframes fadeInUp {
  0% {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(20px);
  }
  100% {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
}
Once you save this file, your custom pink colors, your Inter font, and your fade-in-up animation will all be compiled correctly, and your login button will reappear on the screen!

One last cleanup step: Make sure to completely delete the <script> tailwind.config = { ... } </script> block from the <head> of your HTML file, as Tailwind v4 ignores it and you no longer need it.  
